  "prompt": "What does \"lien amount\" in the SBI mean?",
  "response": "In the context of **State Bank of India (SBI)**, the term **\"lien amount\"** refers to a portion of your account balance that has been **blocked** or **restricted** from being used for withdrawals or other transactions. This is typically done to secure a financial obligation or commitment, such as a loan, credit card, or other banking services.\n\nHere\u2019s a breakdown of what it means:\n\n1. **Why a Lien is Placed**:\n   - SBI may place a lien on your account to ensure repayment of a loan or credit card dues.\n   - It can also be used to secure other financial commitments, like guarantees or overdrafts.\n\n2. **Effect on Your Account**:\n   - The lien amount is deducted from your available balance, meaning you cannot use this money until the lien is released.\n   - The remaining balance (after deducting the lien amount) is what you can freely use.\n\n3. **Release of Lien**:\n   - The lien is removed once the obligation (e.g., loan repayment) is fulfilled or the bank decides to release it.\n   - You may need to contact the bank or fulfill certain conditions to have the lien released.\n\nFor example, if you have a balance of \u20b950,000 in your SBI account and a lien of \u20b910,000, you can only use \u20b940,000. The \u20b910,000 is held by the bank until the lien is lifted.\n\nIf you see a lien amount and are unsure why it\u2019s there, it\u2019s best to contact your **SBI branch** or **customer care** for clarification.",
